		<b>Comment By Anon, 10-31-07</b>
		<p>This is an excellent review. Thanks for writing it. I am going out to buy the book in Bozeman. Keep writing!</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Michael Bartley, 11-01-07</b>
		<p>Bass has long been one of my favorite writers. Friends and I have seen him occasionally at different forums and the art vs. activism arguments that have followed have been interesting and passionate. What happens when a writers activism begins to negatively impact their writing? As some folks feel has happened with Bass. How does a writer achieve balance between their lives (that must infuse their work) and their writing? Can writers separate life from work? I am curious.<br />
Let me just add that I don't believe Rick Bass has lost anything as a writer. The Lives of Rocks is my exhibit A. Extraordinary stories. And, the two stories of Jyl that you highlight are two of the best I have read in a long time. Both moved me to tears. Jyl as a centerpiece of a novel would be exciting. Also, Where The Sea Used To Be is one of the most underrated novels I have ever read. Stonewalls and coffins will never be the same.</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Appelmglokemy, 5-22-09</b>
